# IoT Air Quality & Pollution Monitoring Dashboard

## Abstract

Air pollution has become a major environmental concern affecting public health and quality of life. This project presents an IoT-based Air Quality & Pollution Monitoring Dashboard that monitors air quality, temperature, and humidity in real time. The system utilizes an ESP32 microcontroller, DHT22 sensor, and a simulated MQ135 air quality sensor. Sensor data is processed, classified into AQI categories, logged into CSV files, visualized using Python dashboards, and uploaded to ThingSpeak Cloud for remote monitoring and analytics.

The proposed solution demonstrates the integration of IoT, cloud computing, and data analytics for environmental monitoring applications.

---

# 1. Introduction

Air quality monitoring is essential for understanding pollution levels and their impact on human health. Traditional monitoring systems are often expensive and difficult to deploy on a large scale.

The objective of this project is to develop a low-cost and scalable IoT-based monitoring solution capable of collecting environmental data, generating alerts, and visualizing trends through cloud dashboards.

---

# 2. Objectives

* Monitor air quality continuously.
* Measure temperature and humidity.
* Classify AQI into meaningful categories.
* Generate alerts during unsafe conditions.
* Store environmental data for analysis.
* Visualize data using dashboards and charts.
* Upload data to ThingSpeak Cloud.

---

# 3. System Architecture

The system consists of:

* ESP32 Microcontroller
* DHT22 Sensor
* MQ135 Sensor (Simulated using Potentiometer in Wokwi)
* LED Indicator
* Buzzer
* Python Data Processing Module
* ThingSpeak Cloud Platform

### Workflow

Sensor Data → ESP32 → Python Processing → CSV Storage → ThingSpeak Cloud → Dashboard Visualization

---

# 4. Hardware Components

| Component         | Purpose                |
| ----------------- | ---------------------- |
| ESP32             | Main Controller        |
| DHT22             | Temperature & Humidity |
| MQ135 (Simulated) | Air Quality Monitoring |
| LED               | Visual Alert           |
| Buzzer            | Audio Alert            |
| Breadboard        | Circuit Connections    |

---

# 5. Software Requirements

* Python 3.x
* Pandas
* Matplotlib
* Requests
* Arduino IDE
* Wokwi Simulator
* ThingSpeak Platform

---

# 6. AQI Classification Logic

| AQI Range | Status    |
| --------- | --------- |
| 0 – 100   | GOOD      |
| 101 – 200 | MODERATE  |
| 201 – 350 | POOR      |
| 351+      | HAZARDOUS |

---

# 7. Alert Mechanism

The system generates alerts whenever air quality reaches unsafe levels.

| Status    | Alert    |
| --------- | -------- |
| GOOD      | No Alert |
| MODERATE  | No Alert |
| POOR      | Alert    |
| HAZARDOUS | Alert    |

Actions:

* LED turns ON
* Buzzer activates
* Alert logged to cloud

---

# 8. ThingSpeak Integration

ThingSpeak is used for cloud-based data visualization.

Fields configured:

* Field 1 – Air Quality
* Field 2 – Temperature
* Field 3 – Humidity
* Field 4 – AQI Status Code
* Field 5 – Alert Flag

The cloud dashboard provides real-time analytics and historical data visualization.

---

# 9. Results

The system successfully:

* Simulated environmental conditions.
* Generated AQI classifications.
* Produced CSV logs.
* Created dashboard charts.
* Triggered alerts for unsafe conditions.
* Uploaded data to ThingSpeak Cloud.

Screenshots of the Wokwi circuit, dashboard charts, and ThingSpeak analytics confirm successful implementation.

